# React Admin Boilerplate - Agent Rules (Strict)

## 1) Project Intent
- Build a lightweight, scalable React admin panel.
- Prioritize maintainability, reusability, and clean architecture.
- Avoid unnecessary complexity and over-engineering.

## 2) Dependency Policy (Very Strict)
- Do NOT install any library/package without user approval.
- Before proposing any library, always provide:
  1) Why it is needed,
  2) Pros/cons,
  3) Bundle/performance impact,
  4) Native alternative (if possible).
- Install only after explicit user permission.
- Remove unused dependencies proactively.

## 3) State Management
- Use React Hooks as default (`useState`, `useReducer`, `useContext`, custom hooks).
- Prefer local/component state first.
- Lift state only when required.
- Use Context + hooks for shared app state when needed.
- Redux should NOT be added now.
- If state complexity grows, propose Redux later with justification and ask permission first.

## 4) React Patterns & Standards
- Follow latest stable React patterns and best practices.
- Prefer functional components only.
- Use composition over prop drilling-heavy structures.
- Keep components single-responsibility and small.
- Avoid legacy or outdated React patterns.

## 5) Folder Structure & Reusability
- Always maintain clean, scalable, reusable folder structure.
- Group code by responsibility and feature readiness.
- Suggested structure:
  - `app/` (providers, app-level setup)
  - `routes/` (route definitions, guards)
  - `layouts/`
  - `pages/`
  - `components/` (shared reusable UI)
  - `hooks/` (custom hooks)
  - `services/` (API layer)
  - `constants/`
  - `utils/`
  - `styles/` (tokens/global styles)
- Reuse existing components/hooks before creating new ones.

## 6) Routing Rules
- Use nested routing for layouts.
- Use route guards for protected routes.
- Use `Link`/`NavLink` for internal navigation (never `<a href>` for app routes).
- Keep route paths centralized in constants when app grows.

## 7) Styling & Theme Strategy
- Keep styling lightweight and consistent.
- Use CSS variables/tokens for theming foundation.
- Theme should be configurable later without large refactor.
- Avoid heavy UI/theming frameworks unless explicitly approved.

## 8) Code Cleanliness
- Enforce clean code and coding standards in every change.
- Rules:
  - meaningful naming,
  - no dead code,
  - no unused imports/variables,
  - no duplicate logic,
  - minimal and useful comments only.
- Prefer readable code over clever code.

## 9) Quality Gate Before Completing Task
- Ensure changed files are lint-clean.
- Verify no regressions in routing/layout/basic flow.
- Keep changes focused and minimal to the request.
- Do not modify unrelated files.

## 10) Collaboration Rule
- If architectural trade-offs exist, present options briefly and recommend one.
- For any non-trivial decision (new pattern, package, major refactor), ask user confirmation first.
